Screw dislocation dipole with Burgers vector b=a[1 1 1] in bcc Fe. 
Quadrupolar periodic arrangement.


1) Directory 1_Rotation: 

Rotate elastic constants to obtain their values in the axis
	ex = [-1 -1 2]
	ey = [1 -1 0]
	ez = [1 1 1]	
# babel input_rotation.babel | tee output_rotation.babel

You can apply inverse rotation to check that you get back 
the cubic elastic constants and that the atomic positions 
are the correct ones in cubic axis
# babel input_inverse_rotation.babel | tee output_inverse_rotation.babel


2) Directory 2_Dislocation

Generate dislocation dipole
# babel input_dislo.babel | tee output_dislo.babel


3) Directory 3_VitekMap

Calculate atomic displacement by comparing atomic positions
between the two simulation cells (relaxed dislo dipole and perfect crystal)
# displacement input_vitek.displacement | tee output_vitek.displacement
This generates the file fe_dislo_displacement.xyz

Create necessary files to plot vitek map
# vitek
and then answer to the different questions
or you can directly use the command
# vitek_bcc fe_dislo_displacement.xyz fe_dislo_displacement.xyz 2.850
If the gnuplot script file vitek.gnu already exists, it won't be overwriten

Plot vitek map
# gnuplot vitek.gnu
You can personalize the gnuplot script file


4) Directory 4_NyeMap

Generate file defining crystallographic for bcc crystal
# patternInit input.patternInit

Calculate Nye tensor on each atomic position
# displacement input_nye.displacement

Interpolate data points between atomic positions
using 2D Fourier series
# fourierFit2D < input.fourierFit2D

Plot the result with gnuplot script nye.gnu
# gnuplot nye.gnu


5) Directory 5_VitekNyeMap

Combine Vitek and Nye maps to make a single plot

# displacement input_vitek.displacement | tee output_vitek.displacement
# vitek_bcc fe_dislo_displacement.xyz fe_dislo_displacement.xyz 2.850
# patternInit input.patternInit
# displacement input_nye.displacement
# fourierFit2D < input.fourierFit2D
# gnuplot vitek_nye.gnu


